  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT60-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">piriviṭai āṟṟāmaiyiṟ talaimakaḷ tōḻikku uraittatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Declared to the confidante by HER because of [her] lack of strength in the time of separation.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT60">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                kuṟuntāṭ kūtaḷi rāṭiya neṭuvaraip</l>
<l>                peruntēṉ kaṇṭa virukkai muṭava</l>
<l>                ṉuṭkaic ciṟukuṭai kōlik kīḻiruntu</l>
<l>                cuṭṭupu nakki yāṅkuk kātalar</l>
<l>                nalkār nayavā rāyiṉum</l>
<l>                palkāṟ kāṇṭalu muḷḷattuk kiṉitē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
             <l>Sweet to the mind [is] it often to see the lover,</l>
             <l rend="indent">even if he [is] ungranting, unloving,</l>
             <l rend="indent">as the great honey [is sweet to] the lame one<note place="foot">This is the first example for the elliptical metaphor: the main verb from the emotive level has to be substituted on the figurative level.</note>, seen while sitting</l>
             <l rend="indent">at the long mountain where the short-trunked Kūṭāḷi sways,</l>
             <l rend="indent">who from below<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kīḻ iruntu</term> has to be taken adverbially and related to the place where the lame one stays: below, not on the mountain.</note> forms a little casket with [his] palm,</l>
             <l rend="indent">[and] points [upwards and] licks [his lips].</l>


             
                </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
